Mozilla's Firefox and Thunderbird recently removed 1024-bit certificate aut=
hority (CA) certificates from their trusted store. This change was shipped =
with Firefox 32 on September 2nd. Researchers at Rapid7 Labs discovered tha=
t 107,535 sites are using a certificate signed by the soon-to-be untrusted =
CA certificates <https://community.rapid7.com/community/infosec/sonar/blog/=
2014/09/04/107000-web-sites-no-longer-trusted-by-mozilla>. That is a relati=
vely large number of sites and represents roughly half a percent of all of =
the web sites in our database, but the problem isn't nearly as bad as the i=
nitial numbers indicated - most sites that are active and affected have alr=
eady expired, and shouldn't be trusted on that basis=20
alone. So, the repeal of trust for these certificates is a sound decision b=
ased upon NIST recommendations. We hope that Chrome and other browsers will=
 also remove these certificates to mitigate the potential risk involved wit=
h these 1024-bit CA keys. If you still use a 1024-bit RSA key for any other=
 purpose, such as a Secure Shell (SSH) or PGP, it is past time to consider =
those obsolete and start rolling out stronger keys, of at least 2048 bits, =
and using ECC-based keys where available. Learn more here <https://communit=
