<h2>News</h2>
<p><span><a href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/I030XKY0l4M6Q42M0P0NT00"
>Home Depot was the latest victim</a> in the chain of massive retail store data breaches in the past year.
 The scope and scale of this breach is still unknown and being investigated.
 <a href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/T7QKP0M03000YNY20l4M4T0"
>Lee Weiner, SVP of products and engineering at Rapid7, explains</a> that, &ldquo;the type of data that would have been stolen would be stuff that is captured off your magnetic 
strip.
 That includes your first name, your last name, the expiration date, and the credit card account number.&rdquo; This incident highlights the ongoing troubles that retailers face with cybercriminals.
 Many still remain vulnerable to attacks, particularly through their point-of-sale and back-end software systems.
 Through shadow financial markets, criminals are increasingly able to realize profits from stolen data, so these kinds of attacks aren&rsquo;t going away anytime soon.
 It&rsquo;s important for all organizations handling payment card or personally identifiable information to watch their networks closely for suspicious activity.</span></p>
